		<title>Stay Focused and Get More Done – 11 Computer Apps that Eliminate Distractions</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/energyandmotivation/feed/~3/TnFgKRyIAZY/</link>
		<comments>http://energyandmotivation.com/6041/apps-to-stay-focused/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 29 May 2012 03:41:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Guest Author</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Mindset & Motivation]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Other Stuff]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Computer Apps]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[eliminate distractions]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Productivity Tips]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Work Focus]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://energyandmotivation.com/?p=6041</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[If you do a lot of your work on a computer, I don&#8217;t have to tell you how hard it is to stay focused on your tasks. Too much distraction and lack of focus may often lead to procrastination and loss of motivation&#8230; In this guest post by Ashlee McCullen (of ApronAddicts.com), you may find out about [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- Start Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><!-- End Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><div class="tweetmeme_button" style="float: right; margin-left: 10px;">
			<a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fenergyandmotivation.com%2F6041%2Fapps-to-stay-focused%2F"><br />
				<img src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http%3A%2F%2Fenergyandmotivation.com%2F6041%2Fapps-to-stay-focused%2F&amp;style=normal&amp;b=2" height="61" width="50" /><br />
			</a>
		</div>
<p><em>If you do a lot of your work on a computer, I don&#8217;t have to tell you how hard it is to stay focused on your tasks. Too much distraction and lack of focus may often lead to procrastination and loss of motivation&#8230;</em></p>
<p><em>In this guest post by Ashlee McCullen (of <a href="http://apronaddicts.com">ApronAddicts.com</a>), you may find out about computer applications that can help you stay focused on your work by eliminating distractions.</em> <small>(Photo by <a title="(Tom's Flickr photostream)" href="http://www.flickr.com/people/thomasjoy/">Tom Joy</a>)</small></p>
<p><a title="11 Computer Apps that Eliminate Distractions" href="http://energyandmotivation.com/6041/apps-to-stay-focused/"> <img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-6058" src="http://energyandmotivation.com/wp-content/uploads/iphone.jpg" alt="iphone" width="350" height="233" /></a>Because of their efficiencies, computers make tasks ranging from communication to number-crunching lightning-fast&#8230;</p>
<p>But they also make checking social networks, looking at <a href="http://www.videobash.com/photos">awesome pics</a>, and browsing Reddit.com just as easy. All you need to do in a modern browser is type “f,” and it’ll likely fill in “acebook.com,” adding to your temptations.</p>
<p>So with that in mind, I wanted to share a few apps that are designed to eliminate distractions while you work, or at least help you achieve better focus. (That said, it is important to take strategic breaks.) This list is admittedly Mac-centric, but I’ll point out options for Windows users, as well. <span id="more-6041"></span></p>
<h3>Isolator and ClutterCloak</h3>
<p>Isolator is a simple Mac program that offers a measure of peace among what is normally a sea of overlapping windows. Install this <a href="http://willmore.eu/software/isolator/">free program</a>, and turn it on to darken your entire screen except for the window you’re currently working on. You’ll still see your menu bar, but at least your dock and other open programs are out of sight. You’ll be able to think better with a clear working space, and you’ll be less tempted to absent-mindedly open your browser or check your e-mail.</p>
<p>For the same functionality on Windows, try <a href="http://tomcooke.me.uk/?page_id=5">ClutterCloak</a>.</p>
<h3>WriteRoom and DarkRoom</h3>
<p>Released well before the Mac offered full-screen apps, <a href="http://www.hogbaysoftware.com/products/writeroom">WriteRoom</a> was a pioneer and has spawned imitators. This extremely simple word processor offers the ability to write on a plain black background that takes up your entire screen.</p>
<p>No bouncing e-mail programs. No distracting formatting buttons. Just you and the text. I find WriteRoom fantastic for penning first drafts, as it helps me devote my focus to my writing. Later, I can jazz up an article in Word, but it’s nice having an option as simple as WriteRoom.</p>
<p>Windows users can check out <a href="http://bestuff.com/stuff/darkroom">DarkRoom</a>.</p>
<h3>E-Mail and Social Media Tips and Tools</h3>
<p>As central as e-mail is to what I do, it can be a time-suck as much as a productivity tool.</p>
<p>To keep my account from nagging me, I turned off desktop alerts in Outlook. Then, I created an <a href="http://www.ehow.com/how_2323494_create-email-rules-microsoft-outlook.html">email rule</a> that alerts me if e-mails arrive from a small group of co-workers. This way I can have the best of both worlds: Not being distracted by unhelpful messages, but still knowing when important ones arrive.</p>
<p>On a related note, I highly recommend you turn off all social media account e-mail notifications and instead use<a href="http://nutshellmail.com/"> NutshellMail</a> to keep up with your accounts. This free service provides a daily e-mail with updates for my Facebook, Twitter, and LinkedIn accounts, including new followers and private messages.</p>
<p>Finally, I recommend the excellent <a href="http://hootsuite.com/">Hootsuite social media dashboard</a>. Instead of breaking up your workday to tweet or post on Facebook, schedule posts in advance with this online and app-based tool.</p>
<h3>Browser Plugins: Safari, Chrome, and Firefox</h3>
<p>These days, web browsers are just as important productivity and creation tools as the MS Office Suite, if not more so. That said, it’s easy to get distracted when you’re trying to get serious things done on one.</p>
<p>For Safari users, I strongly recommend “<a href="http://www.mindfulbrowsing.com/">Mindful Browsing</a>.” Once I installed the program and inputted sites to block, I was surprised at how often I would see the plugin’s gateway screen. It turns out my visiting these sites was almost an instinct, just like smoking and overeating are for many people.</p>
<p>Google Chrome users should check out <a href="https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/laankejkbhbdhmipfmgcngdelahlfoji">StayFocused</a> and Firefox users have an excellent option in <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/leechblock/">LeechBlock</a>.</p>
<h4><strong>Wunderlist</strong></h4>
<p>Without a good system for capturing tasks, organizing them, and reviewing them, you may feel a sense of uncertainty. At least, that’s the premise behind the <a href="http://www.43folders.com/2004/09/08/getting-started-with-getting-things-done">Getting Things Done</a> system, which I find to be excellent.</p>
<p>By using a task manager like <a href="http://www.wunderlist.com">Wunderlist</a>, you can take out the uncertainty of knowing what you need to do now and what you need to do next. That in turn will give you an in-the-moment focus that will make you more productive and less likely to be distracted.</p>
<p>I choose Wunderlist because it’s multi-platform and lies within the mid-range between simple and complex to-do programs. (I recommend staying away from to-do programs that are too simple. It’s vital to be able to create a list for what you’re doing now and to keep unrelated tasks out of sight.)</p>
<div class="note">
<p>About the author:</p>
<p><strong>Ashlee McCullen</strong> is a staff writer for <a href="http://apronaddicts.com">ApronAddicts.com</a>, a site about fashionable aprons and kitchen style.</p>
